om","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1236–1290":"circa 1236–1290","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1252–1310":"1252–1310","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1206–Male":"1206–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","27 October 1260":"27 oktober 1260","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","about 1236":"circa 1236","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Hatton, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"about 1236–1290":"about 1236–1290","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1252–1310":"1252–1310","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1206–Male":"1206–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","27 October 1260":"27 October 1260","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","about 1236":"about 1236","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Hatton, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":23,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":54,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Matilda de Bretargh was born about 1236, in Hatton, Cheshire, England, her father, Sir Hugh de Bretargh, was 32 and her mother, Lady Hugh de Bretargh, was 28. She had at least 2 daughters with Adam de Hatton. She died in 1290, in her hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1236–1290":"umbes 1236–1290","1236–1290":"1236–1290","1228–1260":"1228–1260","1252–1310":"1252–1310","1258–1310":"1258–1310","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1236":"1236","27 October 1260":"27. oktoober 1260","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","about 1236":"umbes 1236","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","Hatton, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kin